    slug: "faith-in-predestination",
    description: `Faith in Predestination (Al-Qada wal-Qadar) tackles one of the most intellectually challenging and spiritually profound topics in Islamic theology — the doctrine of divine predestination, which addresses the relationship between Allah's absolute knowledge and power and the human being's free will and moral responsibility. This compact book provides a clear, balanced, and evidence-based explanation of the orthodox Sunni position on qadar, steering carefully between the extremes of the Jabriyyah (who denied human free will entirely) and the Qadariyyah/Mu'tazilah (who granted humans independent creative power that could override divine will). Written for a general audience, the book makes this complex theological subject accessible without sacrificing scholarly precision, drawing primarily upon the Quran, the authentic hadith, and the understanding of the Salaf al-Salih (pious predecessors).

The book opens by establishing the importance of correct belief in qadar as the sixth pillar of iman (faith) — a fact emphasized by the famous hadith of Jibril in which the Prophet (ﷺ) defined faith as including "belief in divine decree, both the good and the evil thereof." The author explains that qadar encompasses four levels: Allah's knowledge of all things before they occur (al-'ilm), Allah's recording of all things in the Preserved Tablet (al-kitabah), Allah's will that whatever He wills must occur and whatever He does not will cannot occur (al-mashiyyah), and Allah's creation of all things (al-khalq). Each level is explained with supporting evidence and common misconceptions are addressed. The book then tackles the question that has troubled believers from the earliest generations: if Allah has already decreed everything, how can humans be held responsible for their choices?

The resolution presented in this book follows the methodological approach of the early scholars — affirming both divine sovereignty and human responsibility without attempting to fully reconcile them through human logic. The author uses the analogy of a ruler who writes a law knowing that certain citizens will obey and others will disobey: the ruler's foreknowledge does not cause the disobedience, and the citizens remain fully responsible for their choices. Similarly, Allah's complete knowledge of what every human will choose does not compel those choices, and every human remains accountable for their actions. The book also addresses the related concepts of rizq (provision), ajal (lifespan), and the tests and trials that Allah decrees for His servants — providing practical spiritual guidance for maintaining trust in Allah's wisdom while striving to earn His pleasure through obedient action. At just Rs.350, this affordable paperback makes essential Islamic theology accessible to every reader, making it an excellent resource for students, teachers, and anyone seeking clarity on one of faith's most demanding subjects.`,
